  <!-- Main Content -->
  <main class="py-12">
    <section class="max-w-screen-xl mx-auto px-6">

      <!-- What is Quick Sort -->
      <div class="section-box">
        <h2 class="section-header">What is Quick Sort?</h2>
        <p class="section-content">
          Quick Sort is a divide-and-conquer sorting algorithm. It works by selecting a 'pivot' element from the array and partitioning the other elements into two sub-arrays, according to whether they are less than or greater than the pivot. The sub-arrays are then sorted recursively.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- How Quick Sort Works -->
      <div class="section-box">
        <h2 class="section-header">How does Quick Sort work?</h2>
        <ol class="section-content list-disc">
          <li><strong>Step 1:</strong> Select a pivot element from the array.</li>
          <li><strong>Step 2:</strong> Partition the array into two sub-arrays: one with elements less than the pivot and the other with elements greater than the pivot.</li>
          <li><strong>Step 3:</strong> Recursively apply the same process to the two sub-arrays until the base case is reached.</li>
          <li><strong>Step 4:</strong> Combine the sorted sub-arrays and the pivot to get the final sorted array.</li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <!-- Time Complexity -->
      <div class="section-box">
        <h2 class="section-header">Time Complexity of Quick Sort</h2>
        <p class="section-content">
          The time complexity of Quick Sort is as follows:
        </p>
        <ul class="section-content list-disc">
          <li><strong>Best case:</strong> O(n log n) - When the pivot divides the array into two equal halves.</li>
          <li><strong>Average case:</strong> O(n log n) - When the pivot divides the array reasonably well.</li>
          <li><strong>Worst case:</strong> O(n^2) - When the pivot is the smallest or largest element (e.g., when the array is already sorted).</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <!-- Advantages -->
      <div class="section-box">
        <h2 class="section-header">Advantages of Quick Sort</h2>
        <ul class="section-content list-disc">
          <li>Efficient for large datasets.</li>
          <li>In-place sorting algorithm (does not require additional memory).</li>
          <li>Average time complexity of O(n log n).</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <!-- Disadvantages -->
      <div class="section-box">
        <h2 class="section-header">Disadvantages of Quick Sort</h2>
        <ul class="section-content list-disc">
          <li>Worst-case time complexity of O(n^2) can occur.</li>
          <li>Not stable, meaning equal elements might not retain their relative order.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <!-- Applications -->
      <div class="section-box">
        <h2 class="section-header">Applications of Quick Sort</h2>
        <ul class="section-content list-disc">
          <li>Used in large datasets where sorting speed is crucial.</li>
          <li>Commonly used in databases and other applications requiring fast sorting.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <!-- Example -->
      <div class="section-box">
        <h2 class="section-header">Quick Sort Example</h2>
        <div class="section-content">
          <p>Consider the array: <code>[10, 80, 30, 90, 40, 50, 70]</code></p>
          <p>Step-by-step sorting:</p>
          <ul class="list-disc pl-6">
            <li>Choose 50 as the pivot.</li>
            <li>Partition the array into two sub-arrays: <code>[10, 30, 40]</code> and <code>[80, 90, 70]</code>.</li>
            <li>Recursively sort both sub-arrays until the array is fully sorted.</li>
            <li>Final sorted array: <code>[10, 30, 40, 50, 70, 80, 90]</code></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

    </section>
